        <section id="eligibility">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">1. Who This Applies To, and Age Requirements</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            We work with adult content creators, so this point matters more than it would for most businesses: you
            must be at least 18 years old to book a project, create an account, or send us any content. By using our
            services, you are personally confirming that you are 18 or older.
          </p>
          <p>
            This also extends to anyone shown in the material you send us. Every person who appears in footage or
            images you submit must be an adult, and you are personally responsible for confirming that and for
            having their consent to have that material edited and returned to you. We do not verify this ourselves —
            we rely on you to be truthful about it, and treating this requirement seriously is a condition of working
            with us at all.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="what-we-offer">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">2. What We Offer</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            We offer video editing, color grading, sound design, and motion graphics services, built around a few
            pricing tiers — Clip, Scene, Feature, and Custom for larger or more involved projects. Each tier is
            structured for a different scope of work and comes with a set number of included revision rounds, so a
            longer or more complex edit gets more back-and-forth built in. You can also add optional extras on top of
            a tier, like rush delivery, captions, a censored preview version, or an intro/outro bumper.
          </p>
          <p class="mb-3">
            The exact pricing and what's included in each tier is shown on our booking page at the time you submit a
            request, and that's the version that applies to your project. We do occasionally adjust pricing as our
            process and turnaround times change, but a price only ever changes for you if we tell you directly —
            once you and our team have agreed on a price for your specific project, that number doesn't move unless
            you ask for something additional.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Clip tier is a no-cost option for eligible creators, limited to one submission per week, requires a
            free account and at least 3 links to your existing profiles or platforms so we can review your audience,
            and carries a visible watermark on the delivered video. See Section 16 for what's required of you in
            exchange for a free edit.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="submitting-a-request">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">3. Submitting a Project Request</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            To start a project, you fill out our booking form with a description of what you want done, which tier
            fits your project, any add-ons you'd like, and links to the platforms or accounts the finished content
            will live on. This gives our team what we need to understand the project and quote it accurately.
          </p>
          <p class="mb-3">
            If this is your first time working with us, we ask that you describe the project and share links to your
            existing content rather than uploading raw files directly at this stage. Once you've completed a project
            with us before, that restriction lifts and you can upload files straight into the booking form going
            forward — up to 20 files per submission, at up to 250MB each. This isn't about not trusting first-time
            clients; it's a practical safeguard against strangers uploading files to us with no relationship or
            payment history behind them.
          </p>
          <p>
            To keep the system fair and prevent spam, anyone submitting a request without an account or a completed
            project history is limited to one submission every 24 hours. Creating an account and building a history
            with us removes that limit.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="pricing-review">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">4. Review and Agreeing on a Price</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            After you submit a request, our team reviews it and gets back to you with a confirmed price for the
            project. For the Clip, Scene, and Feature tiers this is usually close to the listed price plus any
            add-ons you selected; for Custom projects, or anything with unusual scope, we'll work out a fair price
            with you directly based on what you've described. Nothing is charged to you during this review stage.
          </p>
          <p>
            Once a price is agreed, we send you a deposit invoice and your project officially moves into active
            status. You're welcome to ask questions or request adjustments to the scope before agreeing to a price —
            the deposit invoice is the point where the project and price become locked in.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="the-deposit">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">5. The Deposit</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            Once a price is agreed, we invoice you for a deposit equal to 30% of the total project price. This
            deposit secures your spot in our schedule and covers the work that goes into starting your project. The
            remaining 70% is billed later, as the final payment, once your project is finished (see Section 8).
          </p>
          <p class="mb-3">
            Every deposit invoice comes with a due date at least three days out from when it's sent, so you have a
            reasonable window to pay. We'll also send you a reminder if the due date is approaching and it's still
            unpaid.
          </p>
          <p>
            Deposits are paid securely through Stripe, a payment processor used by most online businesses — we never
            see or store your card details ourselves.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="deposit-not-paid">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">6. If the Deposit Isn't Paid in Time</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            If the due date passes and the deposit still hasn't been paid, we treat the project as inactive. It's
            set aside, any files you'd already sent us are moved into secure long-term storage rather than staying
            in our active queue, and the unpaid invoice is cancelled. You'll get an email and an in-app notification
            letting you know this happened.
          </p>
          <p>
            This isn't a punishment and it isn't permanent — it simply reflects that we can't hold an active
            production slot open indefinitely without payment. If you're ready to move forward after this happens,
            just reach out to us and we can pick the project back up.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="delivery-date">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">7. Your Delivery Date</h2>
          <p>
            We set a firm delivery date for your project once your deposit has been paid — not before. This is
            because a realistic delivery date depends on where your project sits in our production schedule at the
            moment work actually begins, and that schedule shifts based on what else is in progress until a deposit
            confirms your project is really going ahead. Once the deposit clears, we'll give you a specific date and
            keep you posted if anything changes.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="revisions">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">8. Revisions</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            Every pricing tier includes a set number of revision rounds — the details are shown on the booking page
            for each tier, and generally scale with the size of the tier, so a Feature-length project comes with more
            included revisions than a Clip-tier edit. A revision round means you review a draft and send back specific
            feedback on what you'd like changed.
          </p>
          <p>
            If you need more revisions than your tier includes, that's not a problem — you can request additional
            rounds at any point, and we'll invoice each one individually at a small fixed rate. There's no hard limit
            on how many extra rounds you can request; we just ask that feedback be specific enough for us to act on
            it, so revisions move the project forward rather than going in circles.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="communication">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">9. Communicating With Us</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            Once your project is accepted and moving forward, direct messaging opens up between you and our studio
            through your dashboard, so you can send notes, ask questions, and share additional reference material as
            work progresses. You can attach files to messages too, up to 10 attachments per message and 1GB per
            file.
          </p>
          <p>
            We expect the same basic respect in messages that we'd extend to you. We reserve the right to limit or
            restrict messaging access on an account if it's used abusively, but that's a last resort, not a default
            posture — the vast majority of client conversations never come close to that line.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="final-payment">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">10. Final Payment and Completion</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            When your project is finished, we send you a final invoice for the remaining 70% of the agreed price.
            Like the deposit, this comes with a due date at least three days out and a reminder if it's approaching
            unpaid. As soon as the final payment clears, your project is marked complete and your finished files
            unlock automatically — there's no separate manual step or waiting period after payment.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="downloading-your-work">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">11. Downloading Your Finished Work</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            Once your project is marked complete, your finished files are available to download from your dashboard
            if you have an account, and also from the project tracking page using your unique project code — even if
            you booked as a guest. There's no expiration date on this access; your files remain downloadable for as
            long as your project stays active in our system.
          </p>
          <p>
            One important thing to know: the project tracking page doesn't require you to log in — it only asks for
            your project code (or your name and email). That's by design, so guests can track and download their
            work without needing an account. But it also means your project code works a bit like a password to your
            finished files, so please keep it private and don't share it anywhere public.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="final-payment-not-made">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">12. If the Final Payment Isn't Made</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            If a final invoice goes unpaid past its due date, the same pattern as the deposit applies: the invoice is
            cancelled and you're notified. Unlike the deposit stage, we give a three-day grace period after that
            before doing anything further, in case you're just working out payment on your end.
          </p>
          <p>
            If three days pass with no new invoice requested, we archive the project and move its files into secure
            long-term storage. Again, this isn't a deletion and isn't final — reach out whenever you're ready and
            we'll pick it back up and get you a fresh invoice.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="pausing-or-withdrawing">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">13. Pausing or Withdrawing a Project</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            If you need to pause a project that's in progress — for example, if your plans change or you need more
            time — you can do that yourself from your dashboard at any point. A paused project stays exactly as it
            is; nothing is deleted, and you can pick it back up whenever you're ready.
          </p>
          <p class="mb-3">
            You can also withdraw a project entirely and delete it from your dashboard. Doing this is permanent for
            any raw files you'd uploaded — source footage, reference material, and chat attachments are wiped
            completely from our systems and can't be recovered. If we had already delivered finished files to you
            before you withdrew the project, we keep a copy of those specific delivered files as a record of what was
            handed over, even though your original raw materials are gone.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is a deliberate, one-way action — please treat it as final rather than a way to temporarily clear a
            project, and use the pause option instead if you might want to come back to it.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="your-account">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">14. Your Account</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            You don't need an account to book a project — you can go through the whole process as a guest and track
            your project by code. Creating an account is optional, but it removes the submission-frequency limit
            described in Section 3, lets you unlock direct file uploads sooner, saves your details so you don't
            have to re-enter them on future bookings, and gives you one place to see every project you've booked
            with us and message our team directly.
          </p>
          <p>
            You can delete your account at any time from your dashboard, which requires you to type your account
            email to confirm — this is a deliberate extra step since the action is permanent. Deleting your account
            wipes the raw files across every project tied to it, the same way withdrawing an individual project
            does, while preserving any files we'd already delivered to you as finished work. If you'd like a copy of
            your account information or project history before deleting your account, just ask us directly and we'll
            get that to you.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="content-you-send-us">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">15. Ownership of the Content You Send Us</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            Anything you upload or share with us — footage, photos, audio, reference material — remains yours. By
            sending it to us, you're giving us permission to view, store, and work with it solely for the purpose of
            completing your project. We don't use it for anything beyond that, and we don't share it with anyone
            outside of the people directly working on your project.
          </p>
          <p>
            You're responsible for making sure you actually have the right to send us whatever you send — whether
            that's because it's footage of yourself, or because you have the necessary permission from whoever is
            shown in it. If a piece of content turns out to involve rights you didn't actually have, that
            responsibility sits with you, not with us.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="finished-work-ownership">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">16. Ownership of the Finished Work</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            Once your final payment clears and your project is marked complete, the finished files we deliver to you
            are yours to use as you see fit. Before that point — while a project is still in progress and only a
            deposit has been paid — the work in progress belongs to us, since it isn't finished or paid for yet. We
            don't publish, repost, or otherwise use your finished work ourselves unless you separately and explicitly
            give us permission to, for example to show as a portfolio piece.
          </p>
          <p>
            Clip-tier projects work a little differently: once a Clip project is marked complete, you agree to
            provide us with either a written testimonial about your experience or explicit permission to publish the
            delivered video (or part of it) in our gallery — whichever you prefer, either one satisfies this. Until
            you do one of the two, you won't be able to submit another Clip project (paid tiers remain
            unaffected).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="content-we-cant-work-with">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">17. Content We Can't Work With</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            We will not accept, edit, or work with any content involving minors in any capacity, non-consensual
            acts, or material that's otherwise illegal to produce or distribute. This is a hard line, not a
            judgment call made case by case.
          </p>
          <p>
            If we discover or reasonably suspect that content submitted to us falls into any of these categories, we
            will immediately stop work, remove the material from our systems, end the project without refund, and
            where required by law, report it to the appropriate authorities. This applies regardless of what stage a
            project is at or what's already been paid.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="platform-responsibility">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">18. Your Responsibility on the Platforms You Publish To</h2>
          <p>
            We edit and deliver your content — what you do with it afterward is between you and the platform you
            post it to. Sites like OnlyFans, Fansly, and similar platforms each have their own content rules, and
            it's your responsibility to make sure whatever you publish complies with them. We're not able to
            guarantee that any finished content will be accepted by a particular platform, and we're not responsible
            for any action a platform takes against your account after you post something we made for you.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="privacy">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">19. Privacy and Confidentiality</h2>
          <p>
            We treat everything about your project as confidential — your identity, your content, and the details of
            what you've booked. We don't discuss your work publicly or with anyone outside the people directly
            involved in completing it, and we don't use your content for our own promotion without asking you first.
            For details on how we handle personal information more broadly, see our Privacy Policy.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="refunds">
          <h2 class="text-white text-xl font-bold mb-3">20. Refunds</h2>
          <p class="mb-3">
            We don't currently have an automatic refund process, and deposits and payments are generally
            non-refundable once paid, since they cover work and scheduling time that's already been committed on our
            end.
          </p>
          <p>
            That said, if something goes genuinely wrong on our side — we can't deliver what was agreed, or there's
            a real mistake in how a project was handled — reach out to us directly and we'll work it out with you in
            good faith. These situations are handled individually rather than through a fixed policy, because the
            right resolution usually depends on the specifics.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="right-to-decline">
